1_0	0.628421	WASHINGTON (AP) _ The Supreme Court struck down as unconstitutional a law giving the president a line-item veto, which let him cancel specific items in tax and spending measures.
1_1	0.13579944	Thursday's 6-3 decision said the law violates a stipulation in the U.S.
1_2	0.22751485	Constitution that requires every bill passed by the Congress to be presented to the president for his signature of approval or veto.
1_3	0.118119	The court said the constitutional language does not allow what in effect would be partial vetoes.
1_4	0.18554851	The justices said that type of line-item veto could be authorized only by amending the Constitution, an arduous process done only 27 times in the document's 211-year history.
1_5	0.52083888	The line-item veto law was challenged by New York City and an Idaho potato growers' group after U.S.
1_6	0.37409701	President Bill Clinton vetoed provisions they sought that were granted by Congress.
1_7	0.29768355	Clinton was the first president to exercise a line-item veto, an authority sought by almost every president this century as a tool to limit wasteful politically based spending by Congress.
1_8	0.2333403	Congress enacted the veto in 1996, and Clinton used it 82 times last year.
