2_23	0.093311295	Thus, he may initiate and influence legislative proposals.
2_24	0.22742341	(footnote 27) Moreover, after a bill has passed both houses of Congress, but ``before it become(s) a law,'' it must be presented to the President.
2_25	0.053723015	If he approves it, ``he shall sign it, but if not he shall return it, with his objections to that House in which it shall have originated, who shall enter the objections at large on their journal, and proceed to reconsider it''.
2_26	0.029200072	Art. I, 7, cl.
2_27	0.14852749	2. (footnote 28) His ``return'' of a bill, which is usually described as a ``veto,'' (footnote 29) is subject to being overridden by a two-thirds vote in each House.
2_28	0.40936816	There are important differences between the President's ``return'' of a bill pursuant to Article I, 7 and the exercise of the President's cancellation authority pursuant to the Line Item Veto Act.
2_29	0.16039608	The constitutional return takes place BEFORE the bill becomes law; the statutory cancellation occurs AFTER the bill becomes law.
2_30	0.092965692	The constitutional return is of the entire bill; the statutory cancellation is of only a part.
2_31	0.18984135	Although the Constitution expressly authorizes the President to play a role in the process of enacting statutes, it is silent on the subject of unilateral Presidential action that either repeals or amends parts of duly enacted statutes.
2_32	0.10005079	There are powerful reasons for construing constitutional silence on this profoundly important issue as equivalent to an express prohibition.
2_33	0.12176171	The procedures governing the enactment of statutes set forth in the text of Article I were the product of the great debates and compromises that produced the Constitution itself.
2_34	0.16880195	Familiar historical materials provide abundant support for the conclusion that the power to enact statutes may only ``be exercised in accord with a single, finely wrought and exhaustively considered, procedure''.
2_35	0.16154171	Our first President understood the text of the Presentment Clause as requiring that he either ``approve all the parts of a bill, or reject it in toto''.
2_36	0.19801193	(footnote 30) What has emerged in these cases from the President's exercise of his statutory cancellation powers, however, are truncated versions of two bills that passed both Houses of Congress.
2_37	0.097978796	They are not the product of the ``finely wrought'' procedure that the Framers designed.
2_38	0.34260097	. . . The Line Item Veto Act authorizes the President himself to effect the repeal of laws, for his own policy reasons, without observing the procedures set out in Article I, 7.
2_39	0.088474713	The fact that Congress intended such a result is of no moment.
2_40	0.25430429	Although Congress presumably anticipated that the President might cancel some of the items in the Balanced Budget Act and in the Taxpayer Relief Act, Congress cannot alter the procedures set out in Article I, 7, without amending the Constitution.
2_41	0.33436497	(footnote 40) . . . If the Line Item Veto Act were valid, it would authorize the President to create a different law, one whose text was not voted on by either House of Congress or presented to the President for signature.
2_42	0.1795936	Something that might be known as ``Public Law 105-33 as modified by the President'' may or may not be desirable, but it is surely not a document that may ``become a law'' pursuant to the procedures designed by the Framers of Article I, 7, of the Constitution.
2_43	0.24242272	If there is to be a new procedure in which the President will play a different role in determining the final text of what may ``become a law,'' such change must come not by legislation but through the amendment procedures set forth in Article V of the Constitution.
2_44	0.16251771	. . . (EXCERPTS FROM DISSENTS FOLLOW IN 2nd TAKE) nn FROM THE DISSENT By Justice Scalia Insofar as the degree of political, ``law-making'' power conferred upon the Executive is concerned, there is not a dime's worth of difference between Congress' authorizing the President to CANCEL a spending item, and Congress' authorizing money to be spent on a particular item at the President's discretion.
2_45	0.089228272	And the latter has been done since the founding of the nation.
2_46	0.0983144	From 1789-1791, the First Congress made lump-sum appropriations for the entire government ``sum(s) not exceeding'' specified amounts for broad purposes.
2_47	0.13362497	From a very early date Congress also made permissive individual appropriations, leaving the decision whether to spend the money to the President's unfettered discretion.
2_48	0.14665153	. . . Examples of appropriations committed to the discretion of the President abound in our history.
2_49	0.2443637	. . . Had the Line Item Veto Act authorized the President to ``decline to spend'' any item of spending contained in the Balanced Budget Act of 1997, there is not the slightest doubt that authorization would have been constitutional.
2_50	0.24198975	What the Line Item Veto Act does instead authorizing the President to ``cancel'' an item of spending is technically different.
2_51	0.10088584	But the technical difference does NOT relate to the technicalities of the Presentment Clause, which have been fully complied with; and the doctrine of unconstitutional delegation, which IS at issue here, is pre-eminently NOT a doctrine of technicalities.
2_52	0.19630939	The title of the Line Item Veto Act, which was perhaps designed to simplify for public comprehension, or perhaps merely to comply with the terms of a campaign pledge, has succeeded in faking out the Supreme Court.
2_53	0.11439491	The President's action it authorizes in fact is not a line item veto and thus does not offend Art.
2_54	0.10533304	I, 7; and insofar as the substance of that action is concerned, it is no different from what Congress has permitted the President to do since the formation of the Union.
2_55	0.098763371	FROM THE DISSENT By Justice Breyer In sum, I recognize that the act before us is novel.
2_56	0.088465613	In a sense, it skirts a constitutional edge.
2_57	0.091193299	But that edge has to do with means, not ends.
2_58	0.095485832	The means chosen do not amount literally to the enactment, repeal or amendment of a law.
2_59	0.13606781	Nor, for that matter, do they amount literally to the ``line item veto'' that the act's title announces.
2_60	0.09685649	Those means do not violate any basic separation of powers principle.
2_61	0.12467451	They do not improperly shift the constitutionally foreseen balance of power from Congress to the President.
2_62	0.10296649	Nor, since they comply with Separation of Powers principles, do they threaten the liberties of individual citizens.
2_63	0.092211979	They represent an experiment that may, or may not, help representative government work better.
2_64	0.12539832	The Constitution, in my view, authorizes Congress and the President to try novel methods in this way.
2_65	0.095042435	Consequently, with respect, I dissent .
